dataIdInfo.idPurp:
Created by: Rio ASE 2023
Created for: CTUIR
Purpose: Upper Walla Walla Watershed Assessment. Model is considered coarse-scale for planning/assessment level purposes.
HECRAS version: 6.3.1
Coordinate system and units: NAD 83 UTM Zone 11 N, system international (metric) units
Outputs: Hydraulic result rasters were created at a variety of flows (described below). Outputs are in metric units (meters for depth, etc.)
Raster naming convention: Tributary (North Fork (NF), South Fork (SF), and mainstem Walla Walla (WW))_Hydraulic Metric (depth, velocity, or shear stress)_metric/imperial_elevationdata (2019/pre-flood or 2021/post-flood)_flowused (refers to recurrence interval of flow (e.g. 2-yr) or low flow (see below))
Terrain: -2021 Post-flood terrain: 2021 LiDAR (1 meter by 1 meter DEM) provided by CTUIR, supplemented with 2016 LiDAR (in Oregon) and 2018 LiDAR (in Washington) in some portions of floodplain within the model domain. -2019 Pre-flood terrain: 2019 LiDAR (1 meter by 1 meter DEM) provided by CTUIR, supplemented with 2016 LiDAR (in Oregon) and 2018 LiDAR (in Washington) in some portions of floodplain within the model domain. Manningâ€™s n: Digitized using terrain data and aerial photography as reference (ortho_1-1hn_s_wa071_2019_1.sid, ortho1-1_hs_s_or059_2017_1.sid, and Walla_Walla_RGBI.sid provided by CTUIR). Manning's n layer considered coarse scale.
Hydrology: Most of flows modeled are representative of discharges at a given recurrence interval (included in the raster name). These flows were calculated for various gages (USGS, WWBWC, and WDOE) within the watershed, and were then interpolated or extrapolated using drainage area as the independent variable. Low flow was calculated in a similar manner, but is associated with the daily average 95% exceedance flow in the summer (from July through September). See Upper Walla Walla River Watershed Assessment and Action Plan (2023) for a detailed description of approach and methods.
